# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-rules-football-card
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-rules-football-card/2003-brownlow-medal] The **2003 Brownlow Medal** was the 76th year the award was presented to the player adjudged the fairest and best player during the Australian Football League (AFL) home-and-away season.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/2003-brownlow-medal] Nathan Buckley of the Collingwood Football Club, Adam Goodes of the Sydney Swans, and Mark Ricciuto of the Adelaide Football Club all won the medal by polling twenty-two votes each during the 2003 AFL season.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/2003-brownlow-medal] Buckley and Goodes polled three votes in matches only twice during the season—the fewest by any Brownlow Medal winner.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/2003-brownlow-medal] The three field umpires (those umpires who control the flow of the game, as opposed to goal or boundary umpires) confer after each match and award three votes, two votes, and one vote to the players they regard as the best, second-best and third-best in the match, respectively.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/2003-brownlow-medal] The votes are kept secret until the awards night, and they are read and tallied on the evening.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] The **American 7s Football League** (**A7FL**) is a sports league in the United States which plays a seven-man version of gridiron football called American 7s Football.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] Launched in 2015, its games are played without football helmets or other protective equipment.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] League players are not paid during the season and most of them are primarily amateurs.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] Instead cash prizes are awarded to division and national champs (divided among the roster of roughly 25 players).
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] For the 2022 season the prize pool was $50,000.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] Founded in 2014 with play commencing the following year, the A7FL plays a seven-game schedule running from March to May, with playoffs running from June to July.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] It can trace it history to a New York metropolitan area league called **Town Beef** that started in 2008 and played 7-on-7 full-contact football with no helmets or pads.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] North Jersey remains one of the two nuclei around which the A7FL's teams are based, the other being the Las Vegas Valley.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] The league primarily attracts semi-professional football players seeking opportunities to stay in shape during spring.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] In 2016, the league participated in a safety study led by the New Jersey Institute of Technology.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] In 2023, the league had its first former NFL starter sign with a team, that being cornerback Dominique Rodgers-Cromartie, who signed with the Tampa Nightcrawlers.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] A7FL players play without pads or helmets as part of what the league describes as an effort to reduce the potential of head injuries resulting from helmet-to-helmet contact.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] League games also do not include kickoffs, field goals, or punts, and, instead of the kickoff, implement a unique version of special teams called a 3-on-1 throw off (three 'throwing' players and one receiver).
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] Games are played on narrow fields of 37 yards' width (34 m, between one set of hash marks and the furthest sideline away) to accommodate fewer players on the field on each team.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] A7FL games are played between two seven-man teams; teams are, additionally, required to cap their rosters at 35 active players.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] Teams that will participate in the 2026 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] Eleven Sports Network acquired the exclusive United States and international rights to broadcast the A7FL 2017 Championship on July 9, 2017, played at Palisades Credit Union Park.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] Through Eleven Sports Network's distribution with DirecTV, Verizon FiOS, and AT&T uVerse the A7FL 2017 Championship was to be accessible by over 70 million homes worldwide.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] In 2018, Eleven Sports Network acquired the exclusive United States and international rights to broadcast a 21-game package including the playoffs and championship, and in 2019, the non-exclusive U.S. and international rights to the playoffs and championship.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] In 2019, Twitch acquired the exclusive United States and international rights to a 21-game package of the season including the playoffs and championship.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] In 2020, A7FL again partnered with Eleven Sports Network for the exclusive United States and international rights of the season, including the playoffs and championship.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] For 2021, FITE TV acquired the United States and international rights to the A7FL's season including the playoffs and championship.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] Starting in 2022, select Games of the Week -- including the playoffs and championship - were broadcast on Stadium (sports network), YouTube, DAZN, and A7FL.tv.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] In 2025, select A7FL Games of the Week including the playoffs and championship and A7FL InMotion, a weekly 30 minute show featuring a look inside the A7FL -- are broadcast on Fox Soul, Stadium (sports network), DAZN, Triller TV, YouTube, and A7FL.tv.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] The CEO of the A7FL is Sener Korkusuz and its president is Ryan DePaul.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] In 2019, UFC co-founder David Isaacs joined the A7FL to serve as chairman of the advisory board.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] Isaacs said, "Removing equipment to make any sport safer seems counterintuitive and we faced similar issues when we launched the UFC and created the sport of mixed martial arts.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] With the A7FL, football can be safer but still thrilling full-contact competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/a7fl] Athletes playing in the A7FL are required to sign a player injury waiver and be 18 years of age or older.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-canberra-p01] The league was founded as the **Federal Territory Australian Rules Football League** in 1924 with founding members Acton and Queanbeyan.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-canberra-p01] The following year, the premiership was contested by 4 clubs including Canberra, Federal and Duntroon.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-canberra-p01] By 1926 the competition had gained popularity and was contested by 5 clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-canberra-p01] In November 2010 the five AFL Canberra Premier Division clubs merged with the Premier Division clubs of the Queensland Australian Football League to form the North East Australian Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-canberra-p01] From 2011 onwards, the AFL Canberra Premier Division together with the reserve sides from the Sydney Swans and Greater Western Sydney Giants would form the NEAFL Eastern Conference.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-canberra-p01] However the NEAFL was later dissolved due primarily to the COVID pandemic and associated financial pressures.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-canberra-p01] The AFL Canberra has been through a number of forms.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-canberra-p01] Clubs listed by highest grade of competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-canberra-p01] Point colours indicate club's highest level of competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-queensland-women-s-league] The **Queensland Australian Football League Women's** (**QAFLW**) is the highest-level women's Australian rules football competition in Queensland.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-queensland-women-s-league] It provides elite women footballers the opportunity to play in a semi-professional environment.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-queensland-women-s-league] Many players from this league have represented their state, earned All-Australian honours, and participated in the AFL Women's (AFLW) competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-queensland-women-s-league] There are five senior women's Australian rules football leagues in Queensland governed by AFL Queensland.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-queensland-women-s-league] The second tier of women's football in South-East Queensland is the Queensland Football Association Women's (QFAW), which was introduced in 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-queensland-women-s-league] This competition is designed to allow women who are new to the game to develop their football understanding and skills, and also provide new clubs with an entry point into women's football.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-queensland-women-s-league] The medal is awarded to the best and fairest player in the league, and was named after Brisbane player Emma Zielke in August 2021.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The **AFL National Championships** is an annual Australian national underage representative Australian rules football tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] Since taking over as national governing body in 1995, the AFL has gradually restructured the competition into a primary junior pathway for its fully professional national club competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The National Championships grew out of the **Teal Cup** which began in Brisbane in 1953 as a junior representative competition between the Australian states of Queensland and New South Wales.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] It was rebranded in 1976 to reflect its expansion to include representative teams from each Australian state and mainland territory, rotated between host cities.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The current competition is contested as a hybrid representative format.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The best players from the academy competitions (AFL club feeder teams) combine to form an 'Allies' team in conjunction with South Australia, Western Australia and two Victoria teams—Metro (Melbourne Metropolitan Area) and Country—to contest the division 1 tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] Originally known as the **Teal Cup**, it was first held in Brisbane, Queensland in 1953 as a junior representative competition between the Australian states of Queensland and New South Wales.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] It was an annual match between the two states, the winners would possess a trophy donated by the Teal family of Queensland.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] Members of the Australian National Football Council, most notably Victorian representative Bruce Andrew, assisted in the establishment the competition in its early days.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The Australian Capital Territory was the first other side to enter in 1973.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] With the addition of teams from each Australian state and mainland territory in 1976, the tournament was rebranded as the **National Championships** and rotated between host cities.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The championships were split into two divisions with the strongest states including Victoria (later split into two sides: Vic Metro and Vic Country) comprising Division 1.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] Papua New Guinea was the first other country to field a team in 1979.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] In the absence of a national league, and less regular senior competition, it grew into one of the most important competitions in the country.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] Early on it was an Under-17 competition, however the age limit has been progressively increased and separate junior championships added for Under-15 level (commencing as the **Shell Cup**, now the **AFL National Development Championships**) from the 1970s onwards.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] It was a major talent pathway for underage players outside Victoria to the VFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] As part of the AFL Commission's role as national governing body, the Victorian TAC Cup competition was restructured in 1992 to become the primary pathway to the AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] As a result, representative development sides from NSW/ACT and Tasmania for a time have played in that competition instead.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] However, in recent years, the National Championships has regained its status as a primary AFL recruitment pathway as the growth of the sport outside Victoria has accelerated.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The division 2 competition was replaced by the Under-19 Academy Series in 2017, with teams from the 4 Queensland and NSW AFL clubs' academies in addition to Northern Territory and Tasmania state teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The entire competition was changed to under-19s in 2021 (the competition has previously operated under-17s and under-18s competitions).
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] With there being no representative football at senior level since 1999, the National Championships are one of the few opportunities for players to play for their state or territory.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] Players typically share the senior team's guernsey (with the exception of Victorian teams, which play in variations of the state team guernsey—Vic Metro has a light blue Big V insignia, while Vic Country plays in a reverse white with navy Big V).
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The best players from the academy competition then combine to form an 'Allies' team in conjunction with South Australia, Western Australia and two Victoria teams, Metro (Melbourne Metropolitan Area) and Country to contest the division 1 tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The winner of the 2024 division 1 tournament was Vic Metro, defeating Vic Country 12.13.85 to 13.6.84.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The **Larke Medal** is awarded to the best player in Division 1 of the competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] It is named in honour of a junior footballer, Michael Larke, who was killed in a bus crash while attending a trial match for New South Wales.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The **Hunter Harrison Medal** is awarded to the best player in Division 2 and is named in honour of a former president and life member of the Northern Territory Football League, Hunter Harrison, who played a major role in the development of the AFL Youth Championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] Each tournament, an underage All-Australian team is named; an MVP is also named for each team.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] Since 2017, the AFL has replaced state and territory representative teams with an academy division consisting of its QLD and NSW AFL Club sides: GWS Giants, Brisbane Lions, Gold Coast Suns and Sydney Swans.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-under-18-championships] The tournament is currently sponsored by the National Australia Bank, having previously been sponsored by Caltex and the Commonwealth Bank.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The AFLW is the second most attended women's football competition in Australia (behind A-League Women) and one of the most popular women's football competitions in the world.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Its average attendance in 2019 of 6,262 per game made it the second-highest of any domestic women's football competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Its record attendance of 53,034 for the 2019 AFL Women's Grand Final was until 2020 the highest match attendance for women's sport in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Since launch, the AFLW has attracted an audience of more than 1 million attendees and 2 million viewers and has managed to maintain high interest while moving to primarily ticketed and subscription broadcasting models since the 2021 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] It consistently ranks in the top three (alongside cricket and netball) most-watched women's sporting competitions in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The league receives international interest, particularly in Ireland, where it has begun to attract a significant television audience due to the ongoing recruitment of Irish Gaelic football stars.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] However, it was reported in mid-2023 that data revealed a significant drop in attendances for the seventh season of the women's league compared to the first season.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] While men playing Australian rules football is documented back to 1858, women's games have only been documented back to 1917, and the first lasting women's league was formed in 1981.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Women's participation in the sport and the prevalence of women's leagues continued to grow into the 21st century.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] In 2010, the AFL commissioned a report into the state of women's football around the country.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Following the report, the AFL Commission began working toward the establishment of a national women's league, choosing to establish women's teams in AFL clubs rather than form separate clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The first on-field step towards the competition took place in early 2013, when the AFL announced an exhibition match to be played between women's teams representing Melbourne and Western Bulldogs in June of that year.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] On 15 May 2013, the first women's draft was held, establishing the playing lists for the two clubs in the forthcoming exhibition match.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The match played on 29 June 2013 marked the first time two women's sides had competed under the banners of AFL clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] A crowd of 7,518 watched the historic match, which Melbourne won by 35 points.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The exhibition match became a series between the clubs, with another game played in 2014 and two played in 2015, the last of which – on 16 August 2015 – was the first women's AFL game to be broadcast on free-to-air television.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] It attracted an average audience of 175,000, surpassing the 114,000 average audience for the AFL men's clash of the previous day, between Adelaide and Essendon.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The success of these exhibition matches prompted the AFL to accelerate its plans for a nationwide women's competition, announcing a preferred start date of 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Prior to this, the league had announced only aspirational plans to have the women's competition established by 2020.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The already-planned 2016 exhibition series was expanded at this time, with a total of ten matches to be played in venues across the country and featuring a range of new temporary representative teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] In 2016, the AFL opened a process for existing clubs to tender applications to join the new competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The 18 clubs in the men's league had until 29 April 2016 to place a bid for a licence, with 13 clubs making bids: Adelaide, Brisbane, Carlton, Collingwood, Fremantle, Geelong, Greater Western Sydney, Melbourne, North Melbourne, Richmond, St Kilda, West Coast, and Western Bulldogs.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The AFL's preferred distribution of clubs was four clubs from Victoria and one each from New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia, and Western Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The inaugural teams were announced on 8 June 2016.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Adelaide, Brisbane, and Greater Western Sydney were the only teams to bid in their respective states and were granted licences to compete in 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Both Western Australian clubs made bids, with Fremantle's bid chosen ahead of the bid from West Coast.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Eight Victorian clubs made bids: Melbourne, Western Bulldogs, Carlton and Collingwood were successful, with Geelong, North Melbourne, Richmond and St Kilda being unsuccessful but granted provisional licences.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Details about the branding of the league were released in the second half of 2016.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] On 15 September 2016, the AFL announced that the league would be named "AFL Women's" or AFLW for short, with the logo being unveiled on 19 September 2016.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The logo is a stylised rendition of an Australian rules football ground goal square and goal posts, drawn from a perspective that resembles a "W".
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] On 10 October 2016, the National Australia Bank was named as the league's naming rights sponsor.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The first premiership game was played at Ikon Park on Friday, 3 February 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The AFL had initially planned to host the game at Melbourne's Olympic Park Oval, with a capacity of just 7,000, but was forced to change to Ikon Park due to overwhelming interest and a need for more seating.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The match was deemed a "lockout" with a capacity crowd of 24,568 in attendance, with estimates of a few thousand left outside.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Gillon McLachlan, the AFL's CEO, personally apologised to those who missed out.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The game was also a great success on TV, attracting a national audience of 896,000, including 593,000 metropolitan free-to-air viewers, 180,000 regional free-to-air viewers, and 123,000 on Fox Footy.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The Melbourne metropolitan audience of 424,000 was on par with that of Friday-night AFL men's matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The inaugural season concluded with the Grand Final held on Saturday, 25 March 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The Adelaide Crows were crowned the league's first premiers after defeating the minor premiers, the Brisbane Lions.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The scoreline read Adelaide 4.11 (35) def.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The remaining AFL clubs would join the league in the follow years, with two clubs added in the 2019 season, four in 2020, and the last four in 2022.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The 10 AFL clubs not originally participating in the competition were invited to bid for inclusion, with priority given to the five clubs that had submitted unsuccessful bids to participate in the inaugural season.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The deadline to lodge submissions was 16 June 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The only clubs not to bid were Port Adelaide and Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] North Melbourne worked with AFL Tasmania to craft its bid, with the club aiming to play home matches in Melbourne, Hobart, and Launceston, and also to select half of its playing list from Tasmania.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] A final decision on which clubs would be admitted to the competition was expected by the end of July 2017, but was delayed several times.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] On 27 September 2017, the AFL announced that Geelong and North Melbourne had been selected to enter the competition in 2019.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] North Melbourne retained its commitment to playing matches in Tasmania.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The league then added four teams in 2020, with the AFL selecting Gold Coast, Richmond, St Kilda and West Coast to join the competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The growth in clubs for the 2019 season was accompanied by the introduction of an American-style conference structure, which was abandoned after the 2020 season in favour of the traditional single ladder.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the 2020 season was curtailed and eventually cancelled without a premiership awarded.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] On 12 August 2021, the final four AFL clubs (Essendon, Hawthorn, Port Adelaide and Sydney) were granted licenses, and the league's seventh season in 2022 was the first to feature all 18 AFL clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] North Melbourne became the first expansion team, founded after the inaugural season, to win a premiership, when the Kangaroos defeated Brisbane by 30 points in the 2024 decider, following this up with a 40 point victory in the 2025 Grand Final rematch.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The competition's 18 teams are based across five states of Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Ten are based in Victoria (nine in the Melbourne metropolitan area), and New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia and Western Australia have two teams each, while a team from Tasmania will enter the AFLW at a date to be confirmed.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory are the only states or territories not to have AFLW teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Below are the venues that hosted during the 2025 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The club's playing lists were constructed from scratch through the later stages of 2016.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] All participants in the 2017 season were required to be over the age of 17.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Initially, clubs were asked to nominate a list of desired players, with the AFL assigning two of these "marquee" players to each club.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] In addition, clubs were able to sign a number of players with existing connections to the club, or with arrangements for club-sponsored work or study.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] This number varied for each club, in an attempt to equitably spread talent across the teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] In addition, clubs were required to recruit two "rookies" – people with no Australian rules football experience in the previous three-year period.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The majority of players were later recruited through the 2016 AFL Women's draft.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The remaining list spots were filled with free-agent signings in the week following the draft.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] In total, clubs have 27 active listed players in addition to injury replacements signed to take the spot of long-term injury-affected players.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Player salaries are determined by collective bargaining agreement with each club's total payments being determined by a salary cap.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] A significant gender pay gap exists between AFL and the AFLW, with the average wage in the women's league being only 16% of that in the men's league as of 2023.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Prior to the commencement of the home-and-away season teams are paired off to play an exhibition trial match.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] In 2017, these matches took place during varying weeks of January.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] For the first two seasons of competition, the home-and-away season was operated on a single table, and seven matches were played by each of the eight teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The two highest-placed teams at the conclusion of the home-and-away season qualified for the Grand Final match, in the absence of a longer finals series.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] With the addition of two extra teams in 2019, the AFL Women's home-and-away season introduced conferences, a concept not common in Australian sports.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The top-two teams from the respective conferences qualified to the preliminary finals, with the first-ranked team in Conference A meeting the second-ranked team in Conference B and the opposite employed for the other preliminary final.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The winners of those matches then met in the Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The use of conferences was retained in 2020, along with the inclusion of four additional teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The 14 teams were split into two conferences of seven, with teams playing each other team in their conference once.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The top-four teams in each conference qualified for the finals series.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The first round of the finals consisted of four knockout finals, with teams from opposite conferences playing against each other, first in Conference A versus fourth in Conference B, and so on.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] This left a final four of North Melbourne, Fremantle, Carlton, and Melbourne, with two rounds of finals to be played.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] At this point, the season was abandoned due to the COVID-19 pandemic, with no 2020 premier.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] In 2021, the league reverted to a single 14-team ladder.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Each team played 9 matches, with the top six qualifying for a three-week finals series.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] All finals are knockouts, with the top-two teams having a bye in the first round of the finals.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Since 2022 (S7) the competition has been contested by 18 teams, and the finals series has expanded to eight teams and is played under the AFL final eight system that has been in use in the men's competition since the 2000 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] On 21 August 2023, incoming AFL chief executive Andrew Dillon announced that the AFLW will receive equal prize money to the AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The prize money for AFLW players will almost double, going from $623,922 to $1.1 million to split between the top 8 teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] In 2018, the Western Bulldogs and Carlton women's teams held the first Pride game, to celebrate gender diversity, promote inclusion for LGBTIQA+ players, and to help stamp out homophobia.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] St Kilda and Melbourne held a Pride Match in 2020, and the first full AFLW Pride Round was held in 2021.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] An Indigenous Round was established in 2021.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] This round acknowledges the significant contribution of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander women and girls to Australian football and the broader community.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Each team wears a guernsey especially designed to celebrate Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander culture, and the Dreamtime match is played between Richmond and Essendon.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] An AFLW Indigenous Round Honouree is announced for each season.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The league peaked at an average attendance of 6,828 in its inaugural season and a record 53,034 attended the 2019 Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Admission was free prior to 2022, when the AFLW introduced reserved ticketing at $10 admission per match, which was later increased.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] In mid-2023, data revealed a significant drop in average attendances for the seventh season compared to the first season.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Taking into account the greater number of games played, total attendance was still growing, just spread over three times as many matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The league's choice of venues has been criticised, with many of the AFL's premium venues, such as Victoria's Melbourne Cricket Ground and Docklands Stadium, not used for blockbuster AFLW matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The league has been cited as preferring the atmosphere of fuller smaller venues rather than emptier larger venues, particularly for its television broadcasting.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] In its inaugural 2017 season, all matches were televised live by affiliate partners the Seven Network and Fox Footy.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] As part of the initial broadcast deal, the free-to-air carrier Seven broadcast one Saturday-night game per week as standard, in addition to the league's opening match and Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Pay TV network Fox Footy televised all premiership season matches, including simulcasts of the Seven-hosted matches other than the Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The two television networks covered the costs of broadcasting these matches, with no licensing fee payable to the league in exchange.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] *Fearless: The Inside Story of the AFLW* debuted on Disney+ in 2022, the docu-series followed several AFLW clubs through the course of the 2022 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] In July 2023 *The Age* reported that AFLW viewer numbers were down 70% from the debut season, blaming a combination of scheduling, poor quality venues and broadcast quality, and "football fatigue".
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The AFLW has attracted an audience of more than 1 million attendees and 2 million viewers and has managed to maintain high interest despite moving to primarily ticketed and subscription broadcasting models from the 2021 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] It consistently ranks in the top three (alongside cricket and netball) most watched women's sporting competitions in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The league receives international interest, particularly in Ireland where it has begun to attract a significant television audience due to the ongoing recruitment of Gaelic football stars.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The official internet/mobile broadcast partner of the AFL is BigPond, part of Telstra.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The company hosts the league website and those of each of the eight participation clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The AFL has retained digital broadcast rights to matches in the league's inaugural season and will stream all matches live and free on the league website and mobile app.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Since 2021, Kayo Sports has streamed all AFLW matches live and on demand in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Outside Australia, the inaugural season is available on Watch AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The National Australia Bank is the league's inaugural and (as of 2022) current naming-rights partner.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] All playing and training equipment, as well as all licensed apparel and hats for the league's clubs, are manufactured by Cotton On.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Other 2017 league sponsors included Wolf Blass, Chemist Warehouse, and Kellogg's.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Official match-day attire, together with other club merchandise, is sold through the AFL's stores and website, as well through the clubs and some retailers.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Prior to the creation of the league, the AFL ran four years of exhibition matches between sides representing Melbourne and Western Bulldogs.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] In 2016, the series was expanded to multiple teams from around the country.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The best and fairest award determined in the same way as the Brownlow Medal for men, with umpires awarding three, two, and one votes to the best three players in each game, and suspended players are ineligible.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] The MVP award is voted on by the players' peers, in a similar method to the Leigh Matthews Trophy for men.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/afl-women-s] Each week, the senior coach of each club gives five votes to the player they consider to be best on ground in the game in which their team plays, four to the second-best, and so on to one for the fifth-best.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:australian-rules-football-card/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] An **Australian rules football card** (colloquially referred to as a **Footy card**) is a type of trading card relating to Australian rules football, usually printed on cardboard, silk, or plastic.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] These cards feature one or more Australian rules football players.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] Cards are almost exclusively found in Australia as no top-level leagues are present outside the country.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] Prices for Australian rules football cards can be very high.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] The first Australian rules football cards were produced in conjunction with Goodwin & Co's Old Judge Cigarettes in the late 1880s.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] Early Australian rules football cards are distinguished from Carte de visite portrait photograph cards as the former were for mass commercial dissemination whilst the latter were often for personal use.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] The Goodwin & Co's Old Judge set included Australian rules footballers from Victoria and South Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] The Old Judge cards are hard to find due to the photographs on the cards fading substantially over time.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] Another set from this period was produced by the American Tobacco Company 'celebrities' from 1894.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] The celebrities set included famous Australians.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] An original copy of a card from this set featured Essendon player Bill Crebbin which sold for $10,110 in 2018.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] Other companies that issued earlier football cards were W.D. & H.O.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] Wills in 1905, and Sniders & Abrahams (featuring scenes of matches in 1908 and then releasing other sets with portraits of football players in the 1910s, all in full colour).
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] Wills also released illustrated sets displaying clubs flags and colours (1908 and 1913) through the Capstan brand.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] In the 1920s one of the most distinctive sets was the 1922 McIntyre Bros cards that featured a tartan design.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] In the 1930s, the Australian division of British Godfrey Phillips Co. released a set of football cards.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] By the same time, Hoadleys, a local confectionery company, released a set of illustrated cards.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] Another confectionery company, Clarke-Ellis, also released its own set of cards.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] Other companies that launched cards sets in the 1930s were Pals Periodical, Plaistowe & Co., Carreras (two illustrated sets in 1933, the first of them with footballers caricatures by Bob Miram), Giant Licorice Cigarettes, MacRobertson's and W.D. & H.O.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] During this period it was common for Australian rules football cards to be sold with confectionary, specifically bubble gum.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] The most popular set of Australian rules football cards is usually considered to be the 1963 Scanlens card set.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] The most valuable card from the 1963 Scanlens set is that of Graham "Polly" Farmer due to its rarity caused by a printing defect seeing many of that card discarded at production.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] A 1963 Scanlens Graham "Polly" Farmer card has been recorded selling for $7,200 on eBay.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] It is not uncommon for single Scanlens cards to sell for more than $1,000.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] A South Australian set produced by AMSCOL featured die-cut cards of SANFL players under the lids of the company's large ice cream tins.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] Due to poor promotion, many people never knew that the cards were included and most were thrown away with the packaging.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] Beginning in the 1990s, packets of Australian rules football cards started to include special inserts such as signature cards.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] In 1991, the Stimorol set was the last issue of Australian rules football cards to come with chewing gum.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] In 1994, Select issued a set called *Cazaly Classics*, after Roy Cazaly, that focused on spectacular marks.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] To coincide with the 100th season of the VFL/AFL competition, Select created a *Hall of Fame* set which is credited with causing a boom in the collecting of Australian rules football cards.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] In 2019, a premium set of Select cards featured an insert card featuring signatures from David Parkin, Leigh Matthews, Kevin Sheedy, and Ron Barassi, all four-time VFL/AFL premiership coaches.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] During 2020, "box breaks" or "group breaks" exploded in popularity for Australian rules football cards, often involving people online buying a 1/18th share of a box, usually aligned to an AFL club.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] As a result of better awareness of the hobby due to social media, there has been an increase in the popularity of Australian rules football cards.
[src:australian-rules-football-card/australian-rules-football-card] Buying cards online has negatively impacted physical card stores.
